# ============================================================================
# SASHA SADR - SESSION 1: "Just Practice"
# ============================================================================
#
# STRUCTURE:
# - Opening & Casual Arrival
# - The "Just Practice" Setup
# - The Moment It Gets Real
# - 4-Card Spread: "What's Really Going On"
#     Position 1: The Surface (2 cards)
#     Position 2: Beneath (2 cards)
#     Position 3: The Other Person (2 cards)
#     Position 4: What You Need (2 cards)
# - Synthesis (conditional based on cards + quality)
# - Payment & Departure (outcome determination)
#
# REVERSALS: 30% chance per card
# INTERPRETATION OPTIONS: 3-4 per card, 1-2 style-gated, rest quality-varied
# HUB CONVERGENCE: After each position, all branches reconverge
#
# Flags in this session:
# discussed_relationship: bool = False
# discussed_pattern: bool = False
# discussed_fear: bool = False
# discussed_jordan: bool = False
# ============================================================================

# ============================================================================
# SESSION START
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session1.Start
~ session = create_session(sasha)
~ session.interpretation_good = 0
~ session.interpretation_okay = 0
~ session.interpretation_bad = 0
~ session.atmosphere = 2
~ session.room_energy = 2
You're in your reading corner. Late afternoon light slants through the blinds.

Your phone buzzes.

**[Text from: Sasha]**
*"heyyy so im outside ur building. this is the tarot thing right?? u said practice. im PRACTICE. 🃏"*

Another buzz.

*"also i brought snacks. u better have coffee."*

@if reader.background == "self_taught":
    You smile. Of course Sasha would make this feel easy. They were your roommate for two years before they moved in with Jordan — they know exactly when you need someone to show up and not make it weird.
@else:
    You smile. Sasha's been texting you since Margaret's reading, asking when they could "be your guinea pig." You've known them since college — old roommate, still one of your closest friends, even after they moved in with their partner Jordan six months back. Today they just showed up.
@endif

+ [Buzz them in with a smile] -> Sasha.Session1.BuzzIn
+ [Text back: "It's not PRACTICE, it's a reading"] -> Sasha.Session1.TextBack
+ [Text back: "What kind of snacks"] -> Sasha.Session1.TextSnacks

:: Sasha.Session1.BuzzIn
You hit the buzzer.

Footsteps on the stairs — quick, taking them two at a time. A thud, a muffled "ow," and then a knock that's more of a drumroll.

+ [Open the door] -> Sasha.Session1.Arrival

:: Sasha.Session1.TextBack
*"omg okay okay SORRY. a ~reading~. very mystical. very serious."*

*"im still practice tho"*

*"buzz me in its cold"*

~ sasha.add_comfort(5)
+ [Buzz them in, laughing] -> Sasha.Session1.BuzzIn

:: Sasha.Session1.TextSnacks
*"trail mix (the good kind with the chocolate chips) and those rice crackers you like. NOW BUZZ ME IN"*

~ sasha.add_trust(5)
~ session.atmosphere += 1
+ [Buzz them in] -> Sasha.Session1.BuzzIn

:: Sasha.Session1.Arrival
**Sasha Sadr** fills your doorway.

Not physically — they're average height, slim build, dark curly hair pulled into a messy bun with a pen stuck through it. Olive skin, sharp nose, warm brown eyes behind chunky glasses that are always slightly crooked.

They fill the space *energetically*. Sasha walks into rooms like the room was waiting for them.

Today: oversized flannel over a band tee (Mitski), ripped jeans, beat-up Docs. A tote bag slung over one shoulder that says "I READ BANNED BOOKS" in faded letters. They're holding a paper bag of snacks and a thermos of what you hope is coffee.

"Okay," they say, kicking off their shoes without being asked. "I'm here. I'm your lab rat. Read my future. Tell me I'm going to be rich and famous and that Jordan is definitely going to—"

They stop. Recalibrate.

"—that everything's going to be great," they finish, too brightly.

You know Jordan. You've had dinner with Jordan. Jordan brought wine to your birthday and seemed perfectly nice. But something about the way Sasha just said their name — the flinch before the brightness, the sentence that got cut off — doesn't match the "we're great, everything's great" version you've been getting for six months.

+ [Note the tone, but don't push yet] -> Sasha.Session1.NotePush
+ ["How IS Jordan? You haven't mentioned them much lately."] -> Sasha.Session1.AskJordan
+ [Let it go, keep things light] -> Sasha.Session1.KeepLight

:: Sasha.Session1.NotePush
~ reader.add_insight(1)
~ session.atmosphere += 1
You file it away. Not the name — you know the name. The *tone.* The way "Jordan" came out like a reflex and got yanked back like a hand from a flame.

Something's changed. The "we're so happy" texts have been getting shorter. The group hang invitations have dried up. You haven't seen Sasha in person in... weeks? A month?

There's a story there. The cards will find it.

"Come in, come in. Coffee?"

Sasha drops their bag on your couch and starts unpacking snacks like they're setting up camp. "Dude, YOUR coffee. I brought the good stuff. French press or drip?"

-> Sasha.Session1.Settling

:: Sasha.Session1.AskJordan
~ sasha.add_trust(-3)
~ sasha.add_openness(-1)
Something tightens behind their eyes. Just for a second.

"Jordan's great! We're great. Everything's—" They wave a hand. "Great. Super great. Anyway! Tarot! Let's do this."

Three "greats" in one breath. That's not how people talk about things that are actually great.

But you pushed too early. The brightness is back, cranked up a notch, and you can feel the door closing.

That's okay. The cards are patient.

"Come in. Coffee?"

"Obviously," they say, and the over-brightness settles to something almost normal.

-> Sasha.Session1.Settling

:: Sasha.Session1.KeepLight
~ sasha.add_comfort(5)
"Get in here, you brought snacks and that's the only qualification I need."

Sasha grins — real, full, the kind that crinkles their nose. "See, THIS is why I agreed to be your guinea pig. Low standards, high snack tolerance."

They drop their bag on your couch and start arranging trail mix in a bowl like it's an art installation. "Okay but seriously, French press or drip?"

-> Sasha.Session1.Settling

# ============================================================================
# SETTLING IN
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session1.Settling
The next ten minutes are just... Sasha.

Coffee gets made (French press, they insist, "drip is for people who have given up on joy"). Trail mix gets arranged. Sasha tells you about their week — the bug at work that took three days to find ("it was a SEMICOLON, {reader.name}, a SEMICOLON"), their landlord's passive-aggressive notes about recycling, a podcast about cults they're obsessed with.

They're good at this. At filling space. At making everything feel easy and warm and slightly chaotic.

You notice they haven't sat down at the reading table yet.

They're orbiting it. Coffee in hand, talking, gesturing, but always angled slightly away from the cards. Like they're circling a pool, testing the temperature with one toe.

+ ["Ready when you are. No rush."] -> Sasha.Session1.GentleInvite
+ ["You know you actually have to sit down for this part, right?"] -> Sasha.Session1.TeasingInvite
+ [Just wait. Let them come to it.] -> Sasha.Session1.PatientWait

:: Sasha.Session1.GentleInvite
~ sasha.add_comfort(5)
~ reader.add_empathy(1)
Sasha looks at the table. At the cards. At you.

"Yeah," they say, quieter than before. "Okay. Yeah."

They sit down across from you. Set their coffee to the side. Tuck a curl behind their ear.

"So how does this work? Do I, like, ask a question? Or do you just... know things?"

-> Sasha.Session1.TheSetup

:: Sasha.Session1.TeasingInvite
~ sasha.add_comfort(3)
Sasha laughs. "Wow, bossy. Is this your reading-room voice? Very authoritative."

But they sit. Pull the chair in. Rest their elbows on the table and their chin in their hands.

"Okay. I'm sitting. Hit me with your mystical wisdom."

-> Sasha.Session1.TheSetup

:: Sasha.Session1.PatientWait
~ reader.add_insight(1)
~ sasha.add_trust(5)
~ session.atmosphere += 1
You sip your coffee. Let the silence be comfortable.

Sasha's monologue slows. The gestures get smaller. The stories run out.

They look at the table.

"...Okay," they say, almost to themselves. They sit down.

Their hands wrap around their coffee mug. Their knee bounces under the table.

"So," they say. "Cards."

-> Sasha.Session1.TheSetup

# ============================================================================
# THE SETUP — "JUST PRACTICE"
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session1.TheSetup
"You can ask a question," you say. "Or you can just let the cards show you what they want to show you. There's no wrong way."

Sasha drums their fingers on the table. Thinking.

"Okay, here's the thing," they say. "I don't actually have, like, a *question*. I'm just here because you needed practice and I'm a good friend and also I was bored."

They pause.

"So just... do a general thing? Like a check-up? 'How's Sasha doing, cards?'"

+ ["A check-up works perfectly."] -> Sasha.Session1.AcceptCheckup
+ ["The cards don't really do 'general.' They find what matters."] -> Sasha.Session1.CardsFind
+ ["Sure — but fair warning, the cards have a way of finding what you're not saying."] -> Sasha.Session1.FairWarning

:: Sasha.Session1.AcceptCheckup
~ sasha.add_comfort(3)
"Cool. Easy. Low stakes."

They lean back, arms crossed, smiling. Totally relaxed.

*They think this is going to be fun and meaningless.*

You pick up the deck.

-> Sasha.Session1.ShuffleIntro

:: Sasha.Session1.CardsFind
~ reader.add_competence(1)
~ sasha.add_trust(3)
Sasha's eyebrows go up. "Oh. Ominous."

"Not ominous. Just... honest. The cards reflect what's actually happening, not what we think is happening."

"Huh." They sit up a little straighter. "Okay. That's... actually kind of cool."

-> Sasha.Session1.ShuffleIntro

:: Sasha.Session1.FairWarning
~ reader.add_insight(1)
~ sasha.add_trust(3)
~ sasha.add_openness(1)
Sasha's smile falters for just a second. Something passes behind their eyes — quick, like a fish in dark water.

"What I'm not saying?" They laugh, but it's hollow at the edges. "I'm an open book, babe. Ask anyone."

*That's exactly what someone who isn't an open book would say.*

"Sure," you say, and pick up the deck.

-> Sasha.Session1.ShuffleIntro

# ============================================================================
# THE SHUFFLE — THE ENERGY SHIFTS
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session1.ShuffleIntro
You shuffle. The cards feel warm in your hands — familiar, alive.

Sasha watches, fascinated despite themselves. "Do you, like, *feel* things when you shuffle? Is it a vibe? A frequency?"

"Something like that."

"Cool cool cool. Very normal."

You spread the cards face-down on the cloth. "Pick four," you say. "Don't think about it. Just let your hand go where it wants."

Sasha reaches out. Their hand hovers over the cards, drifting.

They pick one. Then another. Hesitate over the third — their fingers trembling slightly — then grab it fast, like ripping off a bandaid.

The fourth comes easy. Almost an afterthought.

"Done," they say. "Was that right? That felt weird. The third one felt..." They shake their hand like they touched something hot. "Tingly? Is that normal?"

@if reader.mystical_affinity >= 3:
    You felt it too. The third card *pulled* at them. Not physically — but in the way that certain songs hit you in the chest before you know why.
@else:
    You're not sure what they felt. But their hand is still shaking slightly.
@endif

"That's perfect," you say. "Let me set up the spread."

+ [Arrange the cards with care and intention] -> Sasha.Session1.SpreadSetup

:: Sasha.Session1.SpreadSetup

@py:
# Constrained card pools per position
# 30% reversal chance
deck_surface = Deck(cards=["Two of Cups", "Three of Cups"], reversals=[0.3, 0.3])
deck_beneath = Deck(cards=["Eight of Swords", "Five of Cups"], reversals=[0.3, 0.3])
deck_other = Deck(cards=["The Devil", "Seven of Swords"], reversals=[0.3, 0.3])
deck_need = Deck(cards=["The Star", "Strength"], reversals=[0.3, 0.3])

reading = Reading(spread_id="sasha-whats-really-going-on", decks=[
    deck_surface, deck_beneath, deck_other, deck_need
])
cards = reading.draw_cards()
@endpy

You lay the four cards in a row. Left to right: Surface, Beneath, The Other Person, What You Need.

"Four cards," you say. "What's Really Going On."

Sasha shifts in their chair. "That's the name of the spread?"

"That's the name."

"...Cool. Not terrifying at all."

@render render_reading(reading=reading)

You turn over the first card.

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1Hub

# ============================================================================
# POSITION 1: THE SURFACE
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session1.Position1Hub
@render render_reading(reading=reading)

**Position 1: The Surface — What You're Showing the World**

**{cards[0].get_display_name()}**

@if cards[0].name == "Two of Cups":
    Two figures face each other, cups raised in connection. Partnership. Union. The image of two people choosing each other.

    @if cards[0].reversed:
        But the card is reversed. The connection is strained — something off-balance, a partnership that looks right from the outside but feels wrong from the inside.
    @endif

    Sasha glances at it. "Oh cute. That's like a love card, right?"

    {cards[0].reversed ? "Sort of," you say carefully. "But reversed, it suggests the connection isn't quite what it seems." | "It can be," you say. "It's about how you present your relationships to the world."}

    -> Sasha.Session1.Position1.TwoCups
@else:
    Three figures dance together, cups raised in celebration. Friendship. Joy. Community.

    @if cards[0].reversed:
        Reversed, the celebration feels forced — the performance of fun, the exhaustion of always being the life of the party.
    @endif

    Sasha grins. "Hey, that's me! Party Sasha! The fun one!"

    {cards[0].reversed ? "The fun one," you repeat. "Even when you're not feeling it?" | "The one everyone calls when they need a good time?"}

    "Especially then," they say, and for a moment the grin doesn't reach their eyes.

    -> Sasha.Session1.Position1.ThreeCups
@endif

# --- Two of Cups ---

:: Sasha.Session1.Position1.TwoCups

+ {reader.style == "intuitive"} ["You show the world a partnership. But who's holding the cup higher?"] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Excellent // Excellent
+ {reader.style == "analytical"} [Frame the imbalance with precision — one cup is always heavier] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.ExcellentAnalytical // Excellent
+ ["This card is about connection. You lead with relationships."] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Good // Good
+ ["The Two of Cups represents partnership and love."] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Okay // Okay
+ ["Oh nice, this means you're in love! That's sweet."] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Bad // Bad

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Excellent
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(10)
~ sasha.add_openness(2)
~ reader.add_empathy(1)
"You show the world a partnership," you say. {cards[0].reversed ? "But one of these cups is heavier than the other. You're carrying more than your share — and I think you know whose share you're carrying." | "Two cups raised. But when you said Jordan's name a minute ago, you flinched. You covered it fast, but I saw it. Who's holding the cup higher in that partnership, Sasha?"}

Sasha's smile freezes.

"I didn't *flinch*—"

"You did."

Silence. Their hands wrap around their coffee mug.

"Things with Jordan are..." They stare into the mug. "We're fine. We're totally fine."

~ sasha.discussed_jordan = True

*Fine.* The word people use when they're anything but.

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.ExcellentAnalytical
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(8)
~ sasha.add_openness(1)
~ reader.add_competence(1)
"The Two of Cups is about equilibrium in partnership," you say. {cards[0].reversed ? "Reversed, the balance is off. One person is giving more than they're getting." | "But equilibrium requires both cups to be equally full. If one person is always pouring and the other is always drinking — that's not partnership. That's a job."}

Sasha blinks. "Wow, okay. Getting right into it."

"You said this was a check-up."

"Yeah, but I didn't expect you to find something on the first card." They fidget with a bracelet — braided leather, the kind Jordan made them last summer. You remember Jordan tying it on at the barbecue, the way Sasha beamed. "Things are... it's fine with Jordan. It's fine."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Good
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(5)
~ sasha.add_openness(1)
"This card is about connection," you say. "You lead with your relationships. When people ask how you're doing, you talk about how *they're* doing — your friends, your partner, your people. Your identity is wrapped up in who you love."

Sasha tilts their head. "Is that... bad?"

"Not bad. But it's interesting that the *surface* card — who you show the world — is about someone else. Not about you."

They sit with that for a moment.

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Okay
~ session.interpretation_okay += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(3)
"The Two of Cups represents partnership and love," you say. "It suggests you're in a relationship, or that relationships are a central part of your life right now."

"Yeah, I mean... I have friends. I have a partner. Normal stuff." Sasha shrugs. "Next card?"

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.TwoCups.Bad
~ session.interpretation_bad += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(-5)
"Oh nice, this means you're in love! That's sweet."

Sasha raises an eyebrow. "Did you just say 'oh nice' about a tarot card?"

"I — it's a positive card—"

"Babe, even I know that's not how this works." They're teasing, but underneath it: *you missed something.* The reading hasn't earned their respect yet.

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

# --- Three of Cups ---

:: Sasha.Session1.Position1.ThreeCups

+ {reader.style == "intuitive"} [EXCELLENT: "The life of the party. But who takes care of the life of the party?"] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Excellent
+ {reader.style == "analytical"} [EXCELLENT: Observe the performance pattern — always on, never off] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.ExcellentAnalytical
+ [GOOD: "You show the world celebration. But celebration can be a mask."] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Good
+ [OKAY: "The Three of Cups is about friendship and community."] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Okay
+ [BAD: "Great card! You're surrounded by people who love you."] -> Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Bad

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Excellent
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(10)
~ sasha.add_openness(2)
~ reader.add_empathy(1)
"The life of the party," you say. {cards[0].reversed ? "But reversed — the party's over and everyone went home and you're alone in the kitchen doing the dishes. Who takes care of the one who takes care of everyone?" | "Three cups raised. But you know what I notice? There's always one person in the group who's laughing the hardest, making sure everyone else is having fun. And nobody ever asks them how they're actually doing."}

Sasha's knee stops bouncing.

"That's..." They swallow. "That's a lot from one card, dude."

"Is it wrong?"

Very long pause.

"No," they say quietly. "It's not wrong."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.ExcellentAnalytical
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(8)
~ sasha.add_openness(1)
~ reader.add_competence(1)
"The Three of Cups shows a pattern," you say. {cards[0].reversed ? "Reversed, the celebration is performative. You're expending energy maintaining an image — the fun one, the easy one, the one who's always fine. That's work. And you're not getting paid for it." | "You present as communal, social, light. But the Three of Cups is also about what a group expects from you. You've been cast in a role — the easy one, the bright one — and you play it even when you're exhausted."}

"Okay, *rude,*" Sasha says, but they're not smiling anymore. "When did you get this good?"

"The cards are good. I'm just reading them."

"Uh-huh. Sure."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Good
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(5)
~ sasha.add_openness(1)
"You show the world celebration," you say. "Joy, community, togetherness. But celebration can be a mask. Sometimes the person throwing the party is the loneliest person in the room."

Sasha opens their mouth. Closes it.

"...Okay," they say. "That's — yeah. Okay."

They pick at the trail mix. "Next card."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Okay
~ session.interpretation_okay += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(3)
"The Three of Cups is about friendship and community," you say. "You're someone who values your people. That's your foundation."

"Yeah, totally," Sasha says, brightening. "I love my friends. Next card?"

They relaxed. Which means you didn't reach them. Not yet.

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P1.ThreeCups.Bad
~ session.interpretation_bad += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(-5)
"Great card! You're surrounded by people who love you."

Sasha looks at you flatly. "You sound like a fortune cookie."

"I—"

"Babe. Dig *deeper*. I know you can."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position1.End

# --- Position 1 Convergence ---

:: Sasha.Session1.Position1.End
You reach for the second card.

"Ready?" you ask.

@if sasha.openness >= 3:
    Sasha nods. The breezy energy has shifted — they're leaning forward now, elbows on the table. Present. Listening.
@elif sasha.openness >= 0:
    "Hit me," Sasha says. But the joke has less conviction now.
@else:
    "Sure," Sasha says carefully. Their guard is up.
@endif

-> Sasha.Session1.Position2Hub

# ============================================================================
# POSITION 2: BENEATH
# ============================================================================

:: Sasha.Session1.Position2Hub
@render render_reading(reading=reading)

**Position 2: Beneath — What's Actually Happening Underneath**

**{cards[1].get_display_name()}**

@if cards[1].name == "Eight of Swords":
    A figure stands blindfolded, surrounded by eight swords planted in the ground. Trapped. But — and this is the part most people miss — their hands are only loosely bound. The prison is at least partly self-imposed.

    @if cards[1].reversed:
        Reversed: the blindfold is slipping. They're starting to see the cage for what it is.
    @endif

    Sasha stares at it. The smile is completely gone now.

    "That's... that person looks trapped."

    "They are," you say. {cards[1].reversed ? "But the card is reversed. The blindfold is coming off. Something is shifting." | "But look at their hands. The binding is loose. They could step out of the swords if they saw clearly."}

    -> Sasha.Session1.Position2.EightSwords
@else:
    Five cups lie spilled on the ground. A figure stands over them, head bowed in grief. Behind them — unseen — two cups remain standing.

    @if cards[1].reversed:
        Reversed: the figure is starting to turn. Starting to notice what's still standing.
    @endif

    Sasha's breath catches. Barely audible. But you hear it.

    "That's sad," they say, very quietly.

    "It is," you agree. {cards[1].reversed ? "But reversed, there's a turning. You're starting to look at what survived, not just what was lost." | "But look behind the figure. Two cups still standing. There's something they haven't lost — they just can't see it yet."}

    -> Sasha.Session1.Position2.FiveCups
@endif

# --- Eight of Swords ---

:: Sasha.Session1.Position2.EightSwords

+ {reader.style == "intuitive"} [EXCELLENT: "Underneath the fun, you feel trapped. And you think it's your fault."] -> Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Excellent
+ {reader.style == "analytical"} [EXCELLENT: Map the cage — identify what each sword represents] -> Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.ExcellentAnalytical
+ [GOOD: "The Eight of Swords shows restriction. You feel stuck in something."] -> Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Good
+ [OKAY: "This card suggests some difficulties you're dealing with."] -> Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Okay
+ [BAD: "Don't worry, the swords aren't real threats."] -> Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Bad

:: Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Excellent
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(10)
~ sasha.add_openness(2)
~ reader.add_empathy(2)
~ sasha.discussed_relationship = True
"Underneath the party, the jokes, the 'everything's fine,'" you say, {cards[1].reversed ? "you've been waking up. Seeing the swords for what they are. That's why you're here — not for practice. Something in you knows you need to look." | "you feel trapped. And the worst part? You think it's your fault. The Eight of Swords — the binding is loose, Sasha. You *could* leave. So why don't you? And because you could leave but don't, you blame yourself for staying."}

Sasha's eyes fill.

They don't cry. They hold it. But their jaw tightens and they look away, toward the window, and for a long moment neither of you speaks.

"I don't know how you—" Their voice cracks. They clear their throat. "That's... yeah. That's pretty accurate."

The room is very quiet. Rain against the window. Coffee cooling.

"Do you want to talk about what's got you trapped?" you ask gently. "Or should we let the cards keep going?"

"Cards," they say immediately. "Let the cards do it. I can't—" They gesture vaguely at their chest. "I can't say it out loud yet."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position2.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.ExcellentAnalytical
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(8)
~ sasha.add_openness(2)
~ reader.add_competence(1)
~ sasha.discussed_relationship = True
"Let me name the swords," you say. {cards[1].reversed ? "They're becoming visible to you, which is why you're uncomfortable. Each one is a reason you stay." | "Each one is a reason you stay somewhere that isn't working."} "Fear of being alone — that's one. Habit — two. The belief that it'll get better — three. The idea that you're overreacting — four. Guilt about leaving—"

"Stop," Sasha says. Not angry. Winded.

"I'm sorry. Too much?"

"No, it's—" They press their hands to their face. "It's just really annoying when someone describes your entire inner monologue using a picture of a blindfolded person."

Despite everything, they almost laugh. Almost.

"Keep going," they say through their hands. "I'm fine. This is fine."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position2.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Good
~ session.interpretation_good += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(5)
~ sasha.add_openness(1)
"The Eight of Swords shows restriction," you say. "Under the surface — under the fun, the snacks, the 'just practice' — something has you feeling stuck."

Sasha doesn't deny it. That's telling.

"Stuck," they repeat, tasting the word. "Yeah. That's... a word for it."

-> Sasha.Session1.Position2.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Okay
~ session.interpretation_okay += 1
~ sasha.add_trust(3)
"This card suggests some difficulties you're working through," you say. "Some feeling of being restricted or unable to see your options clearly."

"I mean, who isn't, right?" Sasha says, deflecting. "Late-stage capitalism, am I right?"

The joke lands. But it's a wall, not a bridge.

-> Sasha.Session1.Position2.End

:: Sasha.Session1.P2.Eight.Bad
