"You need to remember your own courage," you say. {cards[3].reversed ? "And reversed — someone has been telling you that you're not brave. That you can't handle things alone. That you need them. And you believed it. But look at this card, Sasha. The lion is powerful and you're holding it with *tenderness*. That's not weakness. That's the hardest kind of strength." | "It's still in there. This card — the woman doesn't fight the lion. She doesn't run. She holds it gently. That's you, Sasha. Your strength isn't force. It's the courage to stay soft in hard situations. But that courage has been buried under someone else's version of who you should be."}

Sasha's jaw works.

"I used to be brave," they say. Very small.

"You still are. You came here."

"That's not—"

"It is. Coming here and sitting in this chair and letting the cards say out loud what you already know? That's the definition of brave."

They cry. Quietly, fiercely, like something breaking open that's been sealed too long.

-> Sasha.Session1.Position4.End

